### Current Behavior

Hello!

Recently we've found a major bug in our code that uses NestJS through Nx, I tracked it down to something build related.
It seems like it tries to optimize the code but does it incorrectly?

```ts
const str = 'str';

if (`${str}${str}` === `${str}str` && true) {
  console.log('hello');
}
```

When the project is built, this code turns into

```js
const str = 'str';
if (`${str}${str}` === `${str}str` && 0) {}
```

It seems to be related to template literals.
This is the simplest form I could shorten it to, but this happens when it's not just one variable.
Every condition in the if after the template literal comparison turns into 0 and the body of the if statement gets removed.

### Expected Behavior

When I tried the same in a NestJS project without Nx, it gave the correct code.

