### Current Behavior

As part of my Next.js app's build process, there are a few files that get generated into the `public` directory. Specifically, a service-worker is generated using the InjectManifest plugin from `workbox-webpack-plugin`, and some files that the App Store and Play Store reference into the `.well-known` directory. The relevant bits of the next.config.js look something like this:

```
      if (!options.isServer) {
        const workboxPlugin = new InjectManifest({
          swSrc: "src/service-worker/index.ts",
          swDest: "../public/service-worker.js",
          // In dev, exclude everything; we don't actually setup caching.
          // This avoids irrelevant warnings about chunks being too large for caching.
          // In non-dev, use the default `exclude` option, don't override.
          ...(options.dev ? { exclude: [/./] } : undefined),
        })
      }
      
      if (!options.dev && !options.isServer) {
        /**
         * Replaces iOS apple-app-site-association stuff dynamically
         * This is required for deeplinking on the iOS app. It's different for prod vs staging environments
         */
        const copyAppleDeeplinkFile = new CopyWebpackPlugin({
          patterns: [
            {
              from: "src/apple-app-site-association",
              to: "../public/.well-known/",
              transform(content) {
                assert(IOS_BUNDLE_ID, "Missing IOS_BUNDLE_ID")
                assert(IOS_TEAM_ID, "Missing IOS_TEAM_ID")
                return content
                  .toString()
                  .replace(IOS_BUNDLE_ID_REGEX, IOS_BUNDLE_ID)
                  .replace(IOS_TEAM_ID_REGEX, IOS_TEAM_ID)
              },
            },
            {
              from: "src/assetlinks.json",
              to: "../public/.well-known/",
              transform(content) {
                assert(ANDROID_PACKAGE_NAME, "Missing ANDROID_PACKAGE_NAME")
                assert(ANDROID_SHA_256_FINGERPRINT, "Missing ANDROID_SHA_256_FINGERPRINT")
                return content
                  .toString()
                  .replace(ANDROID_PACKAGE_NAME_REGEX, ANDROID_PACKAGE_NAME)
                  .replace(ANDROID_SHA_256_FINGERPRINT_REGEX, ANDROID_SHA_256_FINGERPRINT.split(","))
              },
            },
            {
              from: `assets/favicon/${NEXT_PUBLIC_DEPLOYMENT_ENV}`,
              to: "../public/.well-known/",
            },
          ],
        })
        config.plugins.push(copyAppleDeeplinkFile)
```

We just upgraded our repo and app from Nx v13.8 and Next.js v12.10 to 15.9.2 and 13.1.1, respectively. This behavior no longer works. Now, when running either the dev server or building the app and running the prod, these generated files don't get served. Either version of the server serves static files from the `public` directory inside of the app source directory, instead of the build dist output.

We tried to work around this by generating the files into the `public` folder in source, but that ends up creating an infinite compile loop _and_ breaks caching for Nx since there are new source files on every recompile.

It's particularly confusing because the files are still being generated into the same spot in `dist`:

![Screenshot 2023-04-11 at 11 38 57 AM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2012388/231215719-6a6fd1c9-32a3-4903-b2e1-8ea510c517ac.png)

but they're not served. The served files are coming from `apps/spatial-web/public`, as confirmed by editing the files and seeing the changes reflected in the server response.

Doing some digging through the change history of @nrwl/nx, it looks like the regression may have been introduced in https://github.com/nrwl/nx/pull/15861

### Expected Behavior

The development and "local production" Next.js server should serve static files from the `dist/apps/<app>/public` folder instead of from the `apps/<app>/public` folder.

