### Current Behavior

nx module federation promised to decrease build time for local development but the opposite was true once it was developed.

I implemented nx module federation with angular application with ~20 lazy-loaded routes and the initial build time increased from 90 seconds to 30 minutes. 

it appears that with each remote added the initial build time increases by 30 to 90 seconds. Even with just adding the largest 4 remotes it still was 20 minutes for the initial build time. If every developer must do this on the first build of the day there is no performance increase and a performance decrease, a full rebuild would be caused by a number of changes which would be a huge penalty of a 30-minute wait, like changing a script in the package.json file.

I also noticed a significant increase in angular cache sizes. 100 GB sizes of the `.angular` directory were not uncommon.

This is unacceptable and I had to revert the changes of nx module federation in favor of a full build until nx module federation addresses this issue.

my conclusion is nx module federation doesn't scale to large angular applications because each remote needs to load everything the host has. (translations, store, authentication, global services, etc), this duplication in build time on the initial build causes an exponential initial build time increase making the trade-off for incremental build time not worth it.

